Ford GoBike System Data Exploration¶

by Mustapha Olalekan Alaba¶

Introduction¶

This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area for the month of February 2019.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are total of 183412 bike ride record with 16 features. 197 of the rides records are missing the start and end station information. 8,265 of the records are missing the riders member_birth_year and member_gender information.

Integer feature: duration_sec, start_station_id, end_station_id, bike_id, member_birth_year

float feature: start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_latitude, end_station_longitude

String Feature: start_station_name, end_station_name

Datetime: start_time, end_time

Categorical: user_type, member_gender, bike_share_for_all_trip

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm quite interested in figuring out When are most trips taken in terms of time of day and day of the week accross all station and by gender?

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Start time, end time and Gender. I am suspecting more rides will be taking during the weekdays and by male gender. I also think that most rides will be in the morning and evenings not during daytime for weekdays and more rides will happen during work hour at weekends.

Univariate Exploration¶

How are rides distributed accross day of the weeks¶

In [9]:
base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
day_of_week  = ['Monday', 'Tuesday', 'Wednessday', 'Thursday', "Friday", "Saturday", "Sunday"]
sb.countplot(data=gobike, x=gobike.start_time.dt.day_of_week, color=base_color)
plt.xticks(np.arange(0,7), day_of_week, rotation='45')
plt.xlabel('Day of the week')
plt.title('Rides per day of week')


day_of_week_counts = gobike.start_time.dt.day_of_week.value_counts()
total_counts = day_of_week_counts.sum()

#print the proportion text on the bars
for i in range (day_of_week_counts.shape[0]):
    
    count = day_of_week_counts.loc[i]
    # Convert count into a percentage, and then into string
    pct_string = '{:0.1f}%'.format(100*count/total_counts)
    # Print the string value on the bar. 
    plt.text(i, count, pct_string, ha='center')
plt.show()

Our assumption of having more rides during the weekdays is clearly shown in the above chart, we can now take a look at the overall distribution of rides accross hours of the day

We will start with a bin size equivalent to every 30mins from Midnight

In [10]:
# extracting time as a new feature in float between 0 and 24 to see hour trips are distributed during the day.
gobike['hour_of_the_day'] = gobike.start_time.dt.hour + gobike.start_time.dt.minute/60
bins = np.arange(0, gobike['hour_of_the_day'].max()+0.5, 0.5)
def time_of_hist(data, bins):
    plt.figure(figsize=[10, 5])
    plt.hist(data = data, x = 'hour_of_the_day', bins = bins)
    xticks_time = ["Midnight","1AM","2AM","3AM","4AM","5AM","6AM","7AM","8AM","9AM","10AM","11AM","Midday","1PM","2PM","3PM","4PM","5PM","6PM","7PM","8PM","9PM","10PM","11PM","Midnight"]
    plt.xticks(range(0,25), xticks_time, rotation=90)
    plt.xlabel("Time of the day")
    plt.ylabel("Rides counts")
    plt.title("Distribution of rides accross time to the day")
    plt.show()

time_of_hist(gobike, bins)

plt.xticks([1,10,100], [0,1,2])
plt.show()

The log transformation shows that this is a Log-normal distribution.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The duration variable took on a large range of values, so I looked at the data using a log transform. Under the transformation, the data looked symetrical giving a normal distribution.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

When investigating the duration variable, all rides that took longer than an hour was consider as outlier and the dataset contain 1706 of such rides. When plotting the histogram and moving forward the focus was then adjusted to rides that have maximum duration of an hour. The reason for such high ride time should be a separate investigation.

# create tabular form for bar heights
bars_height = []
for i in range(4):
    ind = i*7
    p_heights = [p.get_height() for p in ax.patches[ind:ind+7]]
    bars_height.append(p_heights)

# use pandas to get % from tabular form for bar heights
height_df = pd.DataFrame(bars_height)
height_df_percent = (100. * height_df / height_df.sum()).round(1).astype(str) + '%'

for i in range(4):    
    ind = i*7
    for p_ind, p in enumerate(ax.patches[ind:ind+7]):
        x = p.get_x() + 0.12
        y = p.get_height()
        ax.annotate(height_df_percent.loc[i][p_ind], (x, y), ha='center', va='bottom')

For weekdays, the male percentage was around 71-72% but drops below 70% for saturdays and sundays. other gender have slight increase in percentage for weekends.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

The subscriber user type have rides for 10mins on average while the Customer have higher average time and ride longer during the weekends. The majority of the trips are done by the subscriber.

Conclusions¶

The rides are dominated by male genders, but during the weekends other gender have an increased in percentage of the overall rides. The peak period during the weekdays happens in the morning hour of 8am-9am and in the evening 5pm to 6pm. They is also slight increas in rides count between midday and 1pm. Although the major rides are done by the subscriber with roughly average of 10mins ride duration, the rides done by customers have higher average duration of ride for weekday and even more during the weekends
